(689, '5de61b87a18e9', 'Incidentally diagnosed papillary carcinoma in a thyroglossal duct cyst. What is the next step? A case report and review of the literature', '2019-12-03 09:10:33', '', 3, '  Thyroglossal duct cyst is the commonest congenital disorders of the thyroid gland. Rarely, it can be a malignant tumor that is picked up incidentally in postoperative histopathology. Although management is still a controversy, a careful treatment and follows up planning is necessary for the management of such a condition. We present a case of a 16-year-old female patient with thyroglossal duct cyst carcinoma. ', '', '', '', 201, 'thyroglossal duct cyst. Papillary carcinoma. Thyroid ', 0, 0, 0, '2019-12-03 09:10:33', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(690, '5dfdb92597daa', 'Antilithiasic Effect of Citrullus lanatus Juice on Calcium Oxalate Kidney Stones', '2019-12-21 06:31:31', '', 1, 'Background Nephrolithiasis is a term refers to kidney stones formation, due to aggregation of minerals lead to develop crystalluria in kidney or any part of urinary tract system. Many herbs were used to fragment and crush renal calculi. Habitually, it is noted that people who suffer from kidney problems are advised to eat large quantities of watermellon fruit then, the patient feels healing, without knowing the scientific reason for this improvement.\r\nObjectives The current study was aimed to investigate the antilithiasic effects of FreshWatermelon Juice (FWJ) on calcium oxalate kidney stones. \r\nMethods  Direct exposure technique between FWJ and enucleate stons was used,  the pH value  and electrical conductivity  (EC) of the exposure solution  in addition to studying the chemical and morphological properties of the renal calculi before and after exposure using X-ray diffraction method (XRD) and scanning electron microscope (SEM) investigation. \r\nResults All findings refer to the strong influence of FWJ on renal calculi through a changes in the crystal shape of the calculus which turned into amorphous shape making  it easier to fragment and put out of the body.\r\n', '', '', '', 202, 'Renal calculi, Calcium oxalate, X-ray diffraction, Watermelon, Antilithiasic', 0, 0, 0, '2019-12-21 06:31:31', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(693, '5e23593e5f8f6', 'Magnetic Resonant versus Radiological Skeletal Survey of Lumbo-Sacral Spine in patients with advanced Multiple Myeloma: Single institute experience ', '2020-02-06 09:55:42', '', 1, 'Purpose: Multiple Myelomas (MM) is a plasma cell malignancy in bone marrow (B.M.), where imaging is an essential tool in its management. We aimed to compare the sensitivity of Radiological Skeletal Survey (RSS) with Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) of the Lumbo-Sacral Spine (LSS) in advanced MM patients. \r\nMethod: WE retrospectively reviewed the RSS and MRI of LSS for 33 patients with advanced MM. Data entry and analysis performed  by SPSS program version 25.\r\nResults: 20/13 (60/40%) male/female patients, with a mean age of 61 years. Characteristic findings on RSS were osteopenia (86%), compression fractures (60.5%), multiple lytic lesions (39.5%), solitary focal lesion (4.7%) and normal findings in 9.3%, while that on MRI were combined diffuse and focal lesions (27.3%), multiple focal lesions of macronodular (18.2%), variegated (micronodular) pattern (15.2%), diffuse homogenous infiltration with S.I.> adjacent disc was 12.1% while S.I. < or equal to adjacent disc was 6.1%, solitary focal lesion (6.1%), and normal findings in 15.2%. The majority (58.1%) presented with an advanced stage and pathological compression fracture found in 60% of cases. Focal lesions detected in five patients (15%) whose radiographs were negative, and more lesions detected in 11 patients (33%) with positive radiographs. Diffuse infiltrative-pattern was found in eight cases (24%) when radiographs showed only osteopenia and in one patient (3%) in whom radiographs were normal.\r\nConclusions: MRI had higher sensitivity in the detection of diffuse B.M. involvement and discovery of focal spinal lesions compared to conventional radiographs. \r\n', '', '', '', 206, ' multiple myeloma, radiological skeletal imaging, MRI', 0, 34, 0, '2020-02-06 09:55:42', 0, 0, 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2020-02-06 09:55:42', '', 0),
