(888, '652a528585d98', 'The Role of Interleukin-17 in Chronic Viral Hepatitis B Patients', '2023-10-14 08:50:52', '', 1, 'Background: Hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection often leads to chronic illness, and cytokines have essential roles in viral infections. Interleukin 17 (IL-17) has a role in many chronic inflammatory diseases like pulmonary infection, psoriasis, inflammatory bowel disease, and rheumatoid arthritis, many studies confirmed that the IL-17associated with a progressive inflammation during infection by lymphocytic choriomeningitis virus.  Therefore, IL-17 may play a role during hepatitis B viral infection.\r\nObjectives :The aim of the current study was to determine the serum level of cytokine IL17 in patients with chronic HBV infection in comparison with the levels of this cytokine in healthy controls, assess the correlation between the levels of the cytokine IL-17 and liver enzymes which include Alanin aminotransferase (ALT), Aspartate aminotransferase (AST), Alkaline phosphataselevels (ALP),  Total serum bilirubin (TSB). \r\nMethods: The untreated chronic hepatitis B patients collected from Baghdad-medical-city, Hepatology and Gastroenterology Teaching Hospital, The level of IL -17, viral load, and level of liver enzymes were measured.\r\nResults:Significantly increased in the chronic hepatitis B patients group than the healthy control group (p-value 0.036). This study did not observe any correlation between serum IL-17 levels with ALP, AST, ALT, TSB, and viral load.\r\nConclusion: Our data indicated that serum level of IL-17elevated in patients with chronic hepatitis B, which indicated liver damage and there was no significant correlation between this interleukin (IL-17) with liver enzymes, and viral load.\r\n', '', '', '', 393, 'HBV , IL-17, ALT , AST', 0, 0, 0, '2023-10-14 08:50:52', 0, 0, 5, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
