(920, '65e221e70e056', 'Volumetric Changes in Meningioma After Six-Month Follow-Up of Single Session Gamma Knife Radiosurgery', '2024-03-01 19:02:02', '', 1, 'Background The Gamma Knife Radiosurgery is a type of radiation therapy uses a very intense beam of gamma rays that used in destroying the brain tumors like meningiomas without a need to make a surgical interface. \r\nObjectives This study aimed to determine the effectiveness of the Gamma Knife Radiosurgery in treatment of meningiomas by estimating the changes in meningioma volumes after six months follow up. \r\nMethods In this work, 43 participants data was collected at the Saad Al-Watari Gamma Knife center in Baghdad, Iraq. The data was gathered in December 2021, and the follow-up for each patient lasts for 6 months after the gamma knife surgery.  \r\nResults The outcomes showed that there is a decrease in meningioma volumes of 83.7% of patients. While only 2.3% of the patients recorded no change in meningioma size. Additionally, 9.3% of the patients recorded an increase in meningioma size. And finally, the tumor was completely disappeared in 4.7% of the patients. \r\nConclusions The gamma knife treatment is a beneficial option for reducing the meningioma volume. The study demonstrated that a significant majority of patients experienced a decrease in tumor size. Furthermore, a small percentage of patients reported no change or an increase in tumor size, indicating that gamma knife treatment may not be equally effective for all individuals. However, it is worth noting that two patients reported complete disappearance of their tumors, suggesting a potential for successful tumor eradication with this treatment. \r\n', '', '', '', 420, 'Stereotactic; radiosurgery; Iraq; Brain; Tumor', 0, 0, 0, '2024-03-01 19:02:02', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
