(925, '65f004f63d150', 'Exploring the Correlation Between Tyrosinase Enzyme Levels and the Severity of Melasma in Women: A Case-control Study in Baghdad\r\n\r\n', '2024-03-12 07:52:30', '', 1, 'Background: Melasma is one of the skin problems that causes disruption in facial skin. Tyrosinase enzymes increase and decrease the antioxidants naturally produced in the body, leading to melasma. Tyrosinase (TYR) is a key enzyme in melanogenesis. That increased tyrosinase\'s various mechanisms and genetic, environmental, and endocrine factors.\r\nObjective: To investigate the relationship between serum TYR. enzyme levels and the severity of melasma as a biomarker for diagnosis and treatment.\r\nMethods: A case–control study was executed during the term of March to October 2023; a research investigation has been carried out. (60) patients with melasma and (60) control completed the study (120 females), with an age range of (20-50) years. All participants were examined using Wood\'s light.  Blood samples were collected from each individual, and sera were used after separation to measure TYR by enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) method levels in different stages of melasma severity. \r\nResults: A total 120 samples from melasma women found a significantly increased concentration TYR. with different stages of severity (7.36±0.19 U/ml) compared to the control (3.89±0.08 U/ml) utilizing an independent t-test. Additionally, serum TYR. levels increased significantly as melasma severity increased. Furthermore, the one-way ANOVA test indicated substantial serum TYR MASI levels score for mild, moderate, and severe were 6.19±0.1U/ml, 7.69±0.07 U/ml, and 9.38±0.31 U/ml, respectively. These results strongly indicate that TYR. plays a vital role in the formation and progression of melasma.\r\nConclusion: The results of this study are significant in helping dermatologists develop melasma therapies.\r\n', '', '', '', 426, 'Melasma, Tyrosinase enzyme, melanogenesis, MASI score, ', 0, 0, 0, '2024-03-12 07:52:30', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0);
