(948, '664a1fc20a17b', 'Investigation into the effects of scutellarin against cyclophosphamide-induced testicular dysfunction in Sprague Dawley rats', '2024-05-19 16:12:09', '', 1, 'Background	Cyclophosphamide is one of the most invasive chemotherapeutic drugs, which used commonly despite its adverse effects and toxicities. Scutellarin is an herbal flavonoid with multiple pharmacological activities and clinical applications. \r\nObjective	To investigate whether the scutellarin protect the testes of male rats exposed to a single dose of cyclophosphamide. \r\nMethods	Thirty Sprague- Dawley male rats were divided into three groups: apparently healthy-control group: given normal saline. Induction group: given intragastric normal saline pre and post the intraperitoneal single dose of cyclophosphamide 100g/kg on sixth day. Scutellarin group given intragastric scutellarin 100mg/kg pre and post the intraperitoneal single dose of cyclophosphamide 100mg/kg on sixth day. At the end of treatment, testes are excised after laparotomy to calculate gonadosomatic index (GSI). A blood sample was taken to determine the LH and FSH levels. Testicular advanced oxidation protein products (AOPP) were determined. Harvesting the testes allowed for histological examination. \r\nResults	GSI were notably decline and the LH, FSH, and AOPP levels rised in induced group compared to Apparently healthy control group. Although these measures markedly improve with scutellarin group. Histopathological analysis revealed a substantial change in the testicular tissue structure in the induction group, although scutellarin co-treatment considerably attenuated and even reversed these changes. \r\nConclusion	Scutellarin may act as a protective agent that alleviate rat’s testicular dysfunction caused by cyclophosphamide therapy. The proposed process may attribute to its potent antioxidant property.\r\n', '', '', '', 452, 'cyclophosphamide; scutellarin; gonadosomatic index; gonadotropins; AOPP.', 0, 0, 0, '2024-05-19 16:12:09', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(949, '66538edda6be9', 'The Role of TNF-α and CCL3 Serum Levels in Some Iraqi Colorectal Cancer Patients', '2024-05-26 19:43:18', '', 1, 'Abstract\r\nBackground: The second leading cause of cancer-related death globally, colorectal cancer (CRC) is the malignant neoplasm with the third highest diagnosis rate. It is the primary cause of cancer-related morbidity and mortality in Iraq and ranks second in terms of frequency of death after cardiovascular disorders. An inflammatory cytokine called tumor necrosis factor-α (TNF-α) plays a critical role in the immune response and may contribute to colorectal cancer (CRC) development. Patients with colorectal cancer (CRC) who had elevated serum levels of CCL3 had a worse prognosis than those who had low levels of this chemokine.\r\nAim of study: The study aims to evaluate the role of TNF-α and CCL3 in Colorectal Cancer Patients by Achieving the demographic data analysis of the CRC patients, The serum level estimation of  TNF-α and CCL3 in CRC patients. \r\nMethodology:  The study has been approved by the College of Medical Al-Iraqia University. 100 male and female patients from the Medical City, Al-kadhimiya, and Al-Amal Hospital, and also from a private hospital Al-Bilad Hospital suffering from problems in the colon and rectum participated in this study, they donated 5 ml of their blood which lasted for five months (from November. 2023 until March. 2024). The participants were divided into 2 groups: the 1st one contained CRC patients, while the 2nd contained Colorectal problems other than CRC.ELISA tests for TNF-α and CCL3 serum level estimation were used. Demographic data were collected from the study participants (such as Age, Gender, address, and medical history). \r\nResults: The serum levels of TNF-α and CCL3 in CRC patients appeared to be a significant difference (P<0.05)  compared with the 2nd group.\r\nConclusion: TNF-α and CCL3 significantly appeared as indicators for the progression of CRC cancers.\r\n', '', '', '', 453, 'TNF-Α, IL8, colorectal cancer.', 0, 0, 0, '2024-05-26 19:43:18', 0, 0, 5, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(950, '6654f7c1c9e0a', 'Risk Factors for Chronic Stable Angina and Acute Coronary Syndrome Among Patients Attending Karbala Cardiac Center', '2024-05-27 21:57:41', '', 1, ' Background: Ischemic heart disease is a common cardiovascular disease that occurs when blood flow to the heart is reduced or blocked, leading to a lack of oxygen and nutrients to the heart muscle. It can lead to chest pain, shortness of breath, and potentially life-threatening conditions such as heart attack and heart failure. The two main types are chronic stable angina and acute coronary syndrome.\r\nAim of the study: Evaluate the patients having chronic stable angina and acute coronary syndrome regard the prevalence of risk factors, symptoms, co-morbidities and other factors that may contribute to these differences between the patients.\r\nMethods: A cross-sectional study was conducted at the Karbala Cardiac Center in Iraq. Participants were conveniently selected for the study conducted between January and June 2023. 160 patients diagnosed with IHD were enrolled (60 cases of CSA, 100 cases of ACS). \r\nResults: ACS was twice as common as CSA (62.5% vs 37.5%). There was no significant age difference between groups. More males (67%) than women (23%) were suffered from CSA. ACS patients showed significant dyslipidemia (p=0.002) with increased LDL levels and more frequent medical treatment. Social factors such as retirement and low physical activity were more prevalent among ACS patients. CSA was associated with the emergence of chest pain, while shortness of breath was predominant in ACS.\r\nConclusions: The levels of dyslipidemia, social factors, and symptom presentation varied significantly among the community groups. This result shows the need for individualized management strategies for such conditions.          \r\n', '', '', '', 454, 'Keywords: ischemic heart disease, chronic stable angina, acute coronary syndrome', 0, 0, 0, '2024-05-27 21:57:41', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
