(954, '665c2b3560d56', 'Interference of Coronavirus with Glucose Metabolism and Its Effect on Affinity of Hemoglobin Binding to Oxygen: A Review', '2024-06-02 08:23:30', '', 2, 'Early phases of coronavirus disease-2019 (COVID-19) are characterized by hypoxemic arteries that do not result in gasping, clinical deterioration may occur rapidly if hypoxemia is exacerbated by intra-pulmonary forcing, pulmonary vaso-compression fitness is not managed, and intravascular microthrombi are present with impaired lung diffusion. The goal of this hypothesis is to propose that COVID-19 may interfere with the glycolytic pathway by changing the amounts of intracellular metabolites, especially 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG), to aid in the release of oxygen from hemoglobin into the tissues, therefore preventing or treating hypoxia.\r\nAs a conclusion, focusing on hypoxia as the primary cause of severe morbidity in COVID-19 patients is thought to result from an increased stability of the relax (R-form) of hemoglobin at the tissue level due to a decrease in glucose metabolite produced from glycolysis process in RBCs (decrease 2,3-BPG concentration in the blood). This theory proposes raising 2,3-BPG levels, which is to free up more O2 from the R-form of Hb in the tissues.\r\nKeywords: COVID-19, glucose metabolism, hemoglobin- oxygen binding, 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate\r\nCitation: AbdulKareem NGh, Mohammad FA. Interference of Coronavirus with glucose metabolism and its effect on affinity of hemoglobin binding to oxygen: A review. Iraqi JMS. 2024; 22(1): 1-12. doi: 10.22578/IJMS.22.1.1                                          \r\n', '', 'upload/pdf/iraqijms665c2b3561479.pdf', '', 0, '', 1, 94, 0, '2024-06-02 08:23:30', 0, 0, 3, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Nadia Gh. AbdulKareem, Fatima A. Mohammad', 0),
(955, '665cc729c52c5', 'Knowledge about Risk and Preventive Factors for Knee Osteoarthritis among College Teachers in Baghdad city, Iraq in 2023-2024', '2024-06-02 20:06:10', '', 1, 'ABSTRACT\r\nObjective:-  knee Osteoarthritis is a common musculoskeletal condition that affects the elderly population and leads to decreased mobility. The aim of this study is that  college teachers would  have a good  awareness level  and knowledge about knee osteoarthritis so that they can provide appropriate support and accommodations for themselves and their students with this condition. Methods: - A cross-sectional study carried out at Baghdad/ Iraq from January 2023 until January 2024 in 8 different colleges to assess risks for knee osteoarthritis and the awareness level for a sample of 225 college teachers.\r\nResults: The mean age of participants was 42.1± 10.6 years, 124 (55.1%) of them were males, 132 (58.7%) had PhD degrees and 42% of subject had knee pain. The most frequent risk factor was standing for more than two hours per day with 178 (79.1%) subjects. There were 114 (50.7%) college teachers in this study who showed a good total knowledge score. In our study, the most notable scores pertained to the domains of prevention (83.1% correct) and disability (72.4% correct). In the current study, better awareness was observed in PhD holders. Good awareness levels were more likely to among participants with previous joint injury or disease (odd’s ratio= 2.544), and those who walks >3km/day (odd’s ratio= 3.256).\r\nConclusions: The study highlights standing for extensive periods as a key risk factor for knee osteoarthritis among college teachers, with 42% reporting knee pain. Knowledge was notably better among teachers with PhDs, who participated in lighter physical activities, or walked more than 3km daily. Surprisingly, individuals with physical habits like frequent stair climbing and heavy weightlifting had lesser OA awareness. Additionally, there\'s a noted link between higher OA knowledge and having a history of joint issues or regularly walking long distances.\r\n', '', '', '', 461, 'Preventive Factors, Knee Osteoarthritis, Knowledge. ', 0, 0, 0, '2024-06-02 20:06:10', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(956, '665cdb81c5a5b', 'Salivary Levels of Interleukin-1β and Interleukin-18 as Markers of Pyroptosis in Rheumatoid Arthritis Disease', '2024-06-02 22:27:45', '', 1, 'Background: Rheumatoid arthritis (RA) is a long-lasting, systemic inflammatory disease with an unclear etiology that causes bone and articular cartilage to break down . An innate immune reaction known as pyroptosis fights infection and is crucial to the immune system\'s proper operation. Severe pyroptosis can worsen tissue damage and trigger a hyperinflammatory response, which can result in inflammatory and immunological problems.  This study was performed to evaluates the levels of IL-1β and IL-18 in saliva of RA patients as markers of pyroptosis. Material and Method: Two groups of RA patients (newly diagnosed and treated patients) and a control group were incorporated into this research. Each patient\'s clinical disease activity index (CDAI) was graded by the rheumatologist. We measured the levels of salivary IL-1β and IL-18 using the ELISA method. Result: According to the current study\'s findings, the treated RA group\'s median level of IL-1β was higher than that of the newly diagnosed and control groups, with significant differences (p=0.000). However, there was no discernible variation in concentration between the newly diagnosed group and the control group (p=0.677). The study also discovered that there was no discernible difference in the median IL-18 level across the three study groups (p= 0.118). However, between the treated group and the newly diagnosed group, there were no appreciable variations in the means of IL-1β and IL-18 across the three levels of disease activity (low, moderate, ', '', '', '', 458, 'Rheumatoid arthritis, pyroptosis, cytokines, IL-1β, and salivary IL-18', 0, 0, 0, '2024-06-02 22:27:45', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0);
