(968, '667071b30c775', 'local Hepatitis C Virus isolates reveal a genotype/subtype 4a as determined by E2 sequence variability obtained from Iraqi patients', '2024-06-17 18:16:05', '', 1, 'Hepatitis C Virus (HCV) infection is a significant public health concern globally, with diverse genotypes exhibiting geographical variations in prevalence genotypes and clinical outcomes. 127 clinical samples were collected from Iraqi patients diagnosed with chronic hepatitis C. Viral genomic RNA was isolated and amplified using two primer sets to amplify E2 regions in the HCV genome. The target region of E2 was sequenced using next-generation sequencing technologies, followed by bioinformatic analyses to determine the sequence similarity. The amplicons were sequenced, aligned to a reference sequence, annotated, and submitted to the National Center for Biotechnology Information GenBank (NCBI) database. The sequence of E2 region analysis of the HCV genome showed that the genome size of the tested viral sample was 212 bp. Analysis using bioinformatics tools revealed that these isolates belonged to genotype 4, sub-genotype a. The phylogenetic tree analysis and comparison with global HCV strains revealed that the local strain isolates share ancestry with some isolates from India and Canada and diversity from other isolates from different parts of the world.', '', '', '', 465, 'E2 protein,Hepatitis C virus,genotype 4', 0, 0, 0, '2024-06-17 18:16:05', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(969, '6676734ec2231', 'Investigating the Molecular map of Transfusion Dependant and Non-Transfusion Dependent β-Thalassaemic Patients in Baghdad City ', '2024-06-22 06:59:05', '', 1, '\r\nBackground: β-thalassemia syndrome (BT) is an inherited blood disorder characterized by reduced levels of functional haemoglobin owing to relative reduction or complete lack of β-globin chain synthesis. The severity of the BT phenotype relies highly on the underlying genetic defect affecting β-globin gene. The high prevalence rate, as well as, the severe clinical phenotype frequently associated with patients in the homozygous and compound heterozygous states, have led this syndrome to be one of the foremost significant health burdens worldwide.\r\n\r\nObjective:  the study aims at studying the molecular profile of β-thalassaemic patients in Baghdad city with characterizing the most common β-globin gene mutation among transfusion dependent, and non-transfusion dependent patients\r\n\r\nSubjects and Methods: A cross sectional study was conducted on 80 transfusion dependent (TD) and non-transfusion dependent (NTD) BT Patients. Molecular profiling of BT mutations was performed using β-Globin StripAssay®IME, a reverse-hybridization assay tailored to detect population-specific mutations within the Middle East, Iran, Arabian Peninsula, and India.\r\n\r\nResults: In the current study, 13 different BT mutations have been identified, of which 3 alleles accounted for approximately 60% of the total alleles. These are: IVS 1.110 {G>A} in 44 (27.5%), IVS 2.1 {G>A}:35 (21.9%), and Codon 44 {-C}:14 (8.8%). Other alleles were less frequent including IVS 1.6 {T>C}:11 (6.9%), Codon 36/37 {-T}:10 (6.3%), while the remaining alleles, accounted for 5% or less each. \r\n\r\nConclusions:  The study has revealed a clustering of discrete BT alleles, indicated by the dominance of those alleles in nearly 2/3 of the studied subjects. \r\n', '', '', '', 467, 'molecular map, Allele, beta thalassemia, HBB ', 0, 0, 0, '2024-06-22 06:59:05', 0, 0, 5, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
