(971, '6676db0e41aa3', 'The Role of Pyroptosis in Diabetic Nephropathy: Investigating GSDMD and Biochemical Parameters', '2024-06-22 14:28:20', '', 1, 'Background: Diabetic nephropathy (DN) is a serious consequence of diabetes that can result in end-stage renal failure. The development of this condition is characterized by the activation of inflammatory pathways, in which pyroptosis, a specific type of programmed cell death, plays a vital role. Gasdermin D (GSDMD) plays a crucial role in the process of pyroptosis, which is becoming more and more associated with DN. Elevated glucose levels and advanced glycation end-products stimulate the NLRP3 inflammasome, resulting in the activation of caspase-1 and pyroptosis in different types of kidney cells.\r\nObjective: To investigate the role of pyroptosis in diabetic nephropathy: investigating GSDMD and biochemical parameters\r\nMaterials and methods: This study was case-control study that had 160 subjects divided into three groups including (40 individuals with only DN), 40 individuals with type II diabetes mellitus but without nephropathy (T2DM), and 80 individuals as control group.\r\nResults: The study revealed a strong association between DN and the control group in all investigated parameters. The correlation between DM and the control group did not yield a statistically significant result for GFR), whereas other parameters did reveal significant results. The link between DN and DM is found to be substantial in terms of urea, creatinine, GFR, GSDMD, and IL-18. However, the remaining parameters also exhibit significant results. \r\nConclusion: The significant result in all parameters shown in correlation between DN and control group. The non-significant result in (GFR) in correlation between DM and control group while other parameter shown significant result.\r\n', '', '', '', 468, 'GSDMD, IL-18, DN, T2DM, Pyroptosis', 0, 0, 0, '2024-06-22 14:28:20', 0, 0, 5, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
