(995, '6687115d363f7', 'The Role of Vitamin D deficiency in Pathogenesis of Polycystic ovary syndrome: A case Controlled Study among female in Mosul City', '2024-07-04 22:26:02', '', 1, 'Background: Polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) is commonly endocrine condition primarily affects women of reproductive age. The prevalence of PCOS is 3 to 10%. According to the pathogenesis of PCOS: Obesity, hyperandrogenemia, insulin resistance (IR), hormonal imbalances and metabolic dysregulation are pattern of PCOS, vitamin D deficiency was associated with PCOS and  it has been shown that low vitamin D levels may worsen PCOS symptoms, \r\nObjective: prove the role of vitamin D deficiency in pathogenesis of PCOS.\r\n Methods: A case control study with a sample size of (80).The females included in this study were single or married but not pregnant. The subjects were divided in to 2 groups: 40 females having PCOS and 40 females did not have PCOS, parameters measured are total serum testosterone serum prolactin level and vitamin D level by i-chroma, also body mass index (BMI) (kg/m2) and waist-hip ratio (WHR). \r\n Results: The PCOS group\'s vitamin D levels were significantly lower than those of the control group, significantly higher serum prolactin and  serum testestrone, BMI, WHR among PCOS group, vitamin D among the PCOS group were significantly lower than that among the controls group regarding the married women, with irregular menstrual cycle, presence of acne, androgenic alopecia, hirsutism, positive ultrasound findings, acanthosis, positive family history. There is a weak, indirect significant correlation of vitamin D with BMI (p=0.012) and Serum Testosterone (p=0.015).\r\n  Conclusion: There is a relationship between vitamin D status and a variety of PCOS symptoms, emphasizing the possible contribution of vitamin D deficiency to symptom severity. \r\n', '', '', '', 466, 'Polycystic ovary syndrome, vitamin D, serum Prolactin, serum total testosterone,', 0, 0, 0, '2024-07-04 