(997, '668d7df913004', 'Methods of discarding unused drugs by community pharmacies in Baghdad, Iraq', '2024-07-09 18:22:57', '', 1, 'Background: The disposal of unused medications has emerged as a worldwide concern due to its detrimental effects on the ecosystem and the possible risks it poses to human health and the environment. \r\nObjective: This study aimed to evaluate the techniques utilized by Iraqi pharmacists for the disposal of unused medications and to ascertain the intentions of pharmacists regarding the use of pharmacies as gathering places for potential take-back initiatives. \r\n\r\nMethod: A cross-sectional study was done to assess the knowledge of pharmacists in Baghdad regarding disposal procedures and pharmacy collection points for proper disposal of unneeded pharmaceuticals. Pharmacists from both government and private pharmacies participated in the study.\r\nResults: The study involved a total of 470 pharmacists. 49.1% of the participants indicated a preference for discarding unwanted drugs by throwing them in the garbage, whereas 14% and 9.8% of the respondents recommended disposing of them through waste disposal contractors and pharmaceutical wholesalers, respectively. Based on the medication disposal recommendations of the World Health Organization (WHO), 41.7% of the participants got rid of unnecessary medications. Furthermore, approximately 41.9% had a restricted comprehension of redemption programs. \r\nConclusion: This study determined that pharmacists predominantly adhered to the disposal guidelines set by the World Health Organization (WHO) for the proper disposal of drugs that are no longer needed. There is scope for enhancing the disposal and management of expired pharmaceuticals in Iraq. \r\n', '', '', '', 479, 'unused drug, take back program, medication disposal, pharmacist awareness.', 0, 0, 0, '2024-07-09 18:22:57', 0, 0, 5, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
