(1011, '66f431362d24f', 'The effect of parathyroid hormone on gingival thickness after socket preservation ', '2024-09-25 16:05:04', '', 1, 'Background: Alveolar ridge preservation, also known as ARP, is a preventative treatment procedure that is designed to lessen the amount of hard tissue that is lost after the removal of a tooth in addition to soft tissue thickness can be significantly influenced by the\r\nunderlying hard tissue dimension following tooth extraction.\r\nAim: The aim of this study is to examine the effectiveness of bone graft and parathyroid hormone in terms of soft tissue outcomes (changes in the thickness of keratinized tissue) after socket preservation.\r\nMaterials and methods: In this study there were 16 patients, and all these patients had 32 extraction sockets. The thickness of the gingiva measured before extractions. The patients were then divided into two groups: control group, filled with xenograft only and the study group, where in 16 extraction sockets were filled with xenograft and PTH. Gingival thickness was remeasured after 4 months of treatment. \r\nResults: All the extraction sites were characterized by spontaneous healing. Post treatment also, the PTH and No PTH groups recorded a significant increase in the gingival thickness (p<0.05). However, on comparing the increase in thickness between the PTH group and the non-PTH group, there were no significant difference.\r\nConclusion :using  parathyroid hormone along with a bone graft (xenograft) in a recently extracted socket is effective in maintaining the alveolar ridge, overall bone density, and bone mass. This promotes bone healing for a period of up to 4 months and reduces the amount of soft tissue shrinkage that occurs after tooth extraction.\r\n', '', '', '', 493, 'Gingival thickness, parathyroid hormone, Alveolar ridge ', 0, 0, 0, '2024-09-25 16:05:04', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
