(1018, '670a2b3665691', 'Assessment of Serum Amylase pre and post Bariatric surgery', '2024-10-12 10:39:06', '', 1, 'Abstract :\r\nBackground: Bariatric surgery is prevalent worldwide, including in Iraq. Morbid obesity, on the other hand, has become a global epidemic in the 20th century. Until now, bariatric surgery has been the only effective treatment for this disease, leading to sustained weight loss and the improvement of comorbidities.\r\nObjective: To measure serum amylase pre and post bariatric surgery.\r\nStudy design: This study is a case-control flow-up study.\r\nMethod and Materials: We conducted the study in numerous obesity centers located in Mosul. The study commenced in December 2023 and concluded in May 2024. This study included 50 individuals who were over 18 years old, had a BMI of more than 40 kg/m2, and were ready to undergo bariatric surgery. Serum amylase, if above 100 U/L, would indicate exocrine pancreatic insufficiency.\r\nResult: The mean serum amylase level in the bariatric group (pre-operative) compared to the control group was 56.58±11.53 vs. . 43.30±9.62 U/L (P = 0.0001), and between two independent means bariatric groups (pre- and post-surgery) were 56.58±11.53 vs. 61.64±14.24 U/L (p-value = 0.001).\r\nConclusions: In this study, 8% of the patients complained of increased serum amylase after surgery, and there was a risk of exocrine pancreatic insufficiency after sleeve surgery.', '', '', '', 496, 'amylase, bariatric surgery, obesity.', 0, 0, 0, '2024-10-12 10:39:06', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(1019, '670e95bdf1dc7', 'Role of Medicinal Plants in the Management of Post-COVID-19 Complications', '2024-10-15 16:51:59', '', 2, 'Abstract\r\n\r\nThe pandemic caused by the COVID-19 virus is responsible for these long-lasting consequences, which are collectively referred to as \"Long COVID\" or post-COVID-19 syndrome. These consequences, which include neuropsychiatric symptoms, respiratory issues, chronic fatigue, and circulatory abnormalities, provide significant challenges to healthcare systems all over the world. Because the conventional medical treatments that are now available are unable to provide total comfort, there has been a growing interest in complementary and alternative medicine practices. There has been a lot of interest in herbal treatments because of the possibility that they may be utilized to treat these complex post-viral disorders. Traditional medicine has employed herbs for centuries. The therapeutic properties of medicinal plants are examined in this study. Particular attention is paid to the anti-inflammatory, immunomodulatory, antioxidant, and antiviral activities of medicinal plants. These plants contain bioactive molecules that have the potential to give a number of benefits. The long-term consequences of COVID-19 can be minimized by utilizing these compounds\' capacity to suppress chronic inflammation, control immunological responses, and prevent oxidative damage. Looks like medicinal plants might help COVID-19 patients live longer and recover from their condition more quickly, according to promising results from early clinical and preclinical trials. These findings need to be confirmed by further clinical and mechanistic investigations to guarantee that medicinal plants are safe and effective. A comprehensive medical strategy that addresses patients\' requirements following COVID-19 is highlighted by this study. Evidence-based medicinal herbs should be used with conventional therapy. ', '', '', '', 499, 'COVID-19,complications,mechanisms of action of medicinal plants.', 0, 0, 0, '2024-10-15 16:51:59', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(1020, '671c7c08e49a3', 'Elevated Lactate Dehydrogenase (LDH) Level As A Risk Factor For The Critical COVID-19', '2024-10-26 05:42:52', '', 1, 'Abstract\r\nBackground: Wuhan-China showed an outbreak of respiratory disease caused by RNA virus known as coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19).\r\nAim of the study: establish the level of LDH and CRP and their effect on COVID-19 progress and early detection of critical cases of this disease and predict the mortality rate of the patients.\r\nPatients and methods: The cross-sectional retrospective study consists of 200 CIOVID-19 patients in a privet clinical center in Baghdad-Iraq from February 2021 to February 2022.      Data included age, sex, and clinical presentation. Blood was aspirated for testing high sensitivity CRP and   LDH in the serum.\r\nResults: The enrolled 200 COVID-19 patients were classified into critical 50 patients and severe 150 patients according to clinical signs and symptoms they presented. Laboratory tests (LDH and CRP) showed a significant increase (P=0.000) in critical patients who need admission to the respiratory care unit and mechanical ventilation than in patients with severe COVID-19 (760.5±6.3 vs. 290.3±4.1 and 44.9±7.6 vs. 25.4±2.3 respectively)\r\nConclusions: LDH and CRP showed a significant increase in critical COVID-19 patients which may be considered as a risk factor for predicting the bad progression of the disease. \r\n', '', '', '', 500, 'LDH, COVID, severity', 0, 0, 0, '2024-10-26 05:42:52', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
