(1022, '6720cad280fad', 'Emerging Roles of ADAM Proteases and MicroRNAs in Colorectal Cancer Immune Evasion and Pathogenesis', '2024-10-29 18:45:08', '', 2, 'Colorectal cancer (CRC) is among the leading malignancies worldwide, characterized by complex interactions within the tumor microenvironment that support growth, metastasis, and immune evasion. This review synthesizes current knowledge on the roles of A Disintegrin and Metalloproteinase (ADAM) proteases and microRNAs (miRNAs) in the progression and immune modulation of CRC. ADAM proteases contribute to the shedding of immune-stimulatory molecules, aiding tumor cells in evading immune detection, while miRNAs serve as critical regulators of various oncogenic pathways, including those controlling protease activity. Together, ADAM proteases and miRNAs are involved in reshaping the immune landscape of CRC, influencing tumor immunogenicity and response to therapies. We explore the mechanisms by which ADAM proteases and miRNAs facilitate CRC immune evasion, their potential as biomarkers for early detection, and their promise as therapeutic targets to counteract immune escape and improve patient outcomes. This review highlights key advances and outlines future directions for research aimed at leveraging these molecules to enhance CRC management and treatment strategies.', '', '', '', 498, 'CRC, Immune Evasion, ADAMs, MicroRNAs, Biomarkers', 0, 0, 0, '2024-10-29 18:45:08', 0, 0, 5, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(1023, '672109e4af9ed', 'Sarcopenia Frequency Among a Sample of Iraqi \r\nCOVID-19 Survivors/ a single center study', '2024-10-29 16:15:52', '', 1, '', '', '', '', 501, '', 0, 0, 0, '2024-10-29 16:15:52', 0, 0, 5, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(1024, '67210aac1996c', 'Sarcopenia Frequency Among a Sample of Iraqi \r\nCOVID-19 Survivors/ a single center study', '2024-10-29 16:33:48', '', 1, 'Coronavirus disease 2019 induced by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus-2 had a negative impact on health worldwide, most obvious in its acute stage, but more subtle chronic sequelae are being recognized. Sarcopenia, a progressive loss of muscle mass and strength, is believed to be both a risk factor and a complication of acute COVID-19 in various settings. The virus induced inflammatory state may facilitate sarcopenia development. Objectives To assess sarcopenia frequency following COVID-19 infection and to study the effect of various patient and infection-related factors on its development. Methods An observational cross-sectional study, conducted at Baghdad Teaching Hospital from December 2021 until June 2022. A convenience sample of PCR-confirmed COVID-19 infection survivors who were otherwise apparently healthy was recruited, patients’ data were collected by direct questioning with measurements of muscle mass, strength and physical performance to determine sarcopenia category. Results The study included 68 participants, with a mean age of 37.32 ± (SD 10.98) years. Severe COVID-19 infection occurred in 17.6% while 82.4% had a non-severe infection. The frequency of sarcopenia was 6%, and probable sarcopenia 12%. No cases of severe sarcopenia were recorded. The study showed a significant association between sarcopenia and a BMI < 25 (P value 0.023), and between steroid use and probable sarcopenia (P value 0.013). Conclusion sarcopenia is common, and probable sarcopenia is very common following COVID-19. Having a BMI within the normal range increases the risk of developing sarcopenia and corticosteroid use increases the risk of developing probable sarcopenia.\r\n', '', '', '', 501, 'Sarcopenia, COVID-19, corticosteroids', 0, 0, 0, '2024-10-29 16:33:48', 0, 0, 5, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(1025, '67239c10bd222', 'Sarcopenia Frequency Among a Sample of Iraqi \r\nCOVID-19 Survivors/ a single center study', '2024-10-31 15:11:44', '', 1, 'Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) induced by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus-2 had a massive negative impact on healthcare systems worldwide, most obvious in its acute stage, but more subtle chronic sequelae are being recognized. Sarcopenia, a progressive loss of muscle mass and strength, can be both a risk factor and a complication of acute COVID-19. Sarcopenia complicates various inflammatory illnesses, and the inflammatory state induced by COVID may facilitate its development. Objectives To assess sarcopenia frequency following COVID-19 infection and to study the effect of various patient- and infection-related factors on its development. Methods An observational cross-sectional study, conducted at Baghdad Teaching Hospital in Baghdad, Iraq, from December 2021 until June 2022. A convenience sample of PCR-confirmed COVID-19 infection survivors who were otherwise apparently healthy was recruited, patients’ data were collected by direct questioning with measurements of muscle mass, strength and physical performance to determine sarcopenia category. Results The study included 68 participants, with a mean age of 37.32 ± (SD 10.98) years. Severe COVID-19 infection occurred in 17.6% while 82.4% had a non-severe infection. The frequency of sarcopenia was 6%, and probable sarcopenia 12% . No cases of severe sarcopenia were recorded. The study showed a significant association between sarcopenia and a BMI < 25 (P value 0.023), and between steroid use and probable sarcopenia (P value 0.013). Conclusion Sarcopenia is common, and probable sarcopenia is very common following COVID-19. Having a normal BMI increases the risk of developing sarcopenia and corticosteroid use increases risk of developing probable sarcopenia.', '', '', '', 501, 'Sarcopenia, COVID-19, Complications, Long COVID, corticosteroids', 0, 0, 0, '2024-10-31 15:11:44', 0, 0, 5, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
