(1027, '6731b59442470', 'Awareness about subcutaneous Anti- Tumor Necrosis Factors Alpha medications in a sample of Iraqi patients with Rheumatoid Arthritis', '2024-11-17 08:33:09', '', 1, 'Background: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA) is a chronic autoimmune disorder that might lead to progressive joints destruction and disability. Anti-Tumor Necrosis Factor alpha (anti-TNF-α) is one of many drugs used to treat RA. Level of patients\' awareness about anti-TNF-α has not been adequately evaluated.\r\n\r\nObjective: to assess the level of awareness of patients with RA on subcutaneous anti-TNF-α medications and determine the impact of socio-demographic and clinical characteristics of the patients on their level of awareness.\r\nMethods: total of 170 RA patients using subcutaneous anti-TNF-α medications were included. The data were collected by questionnaire through patient interview. The questionnaires had three parts; first part was about demographic and lifestyle behaviors. Second part was about patients\' clinical characteristics, disease duration, type and duration of anti-TNF-α , and others. Third part consisted of 13 questions to evaluate the patients\' awareness about anti-TNF-α.\r\nResults: The majority (52.32%) of patients had good level of awareness, 30.95% had partial awareness and 16.73% were poorly aware about medications. Lowest scores questions were about anti-TNF-α side effects and patient behavior in case of missing a dose. There was no significant impact of socio-demographic, clinical characteristics, and type and duration of anti-TNF-α on total awareness score.\r\n\r\nConclusions: there was a fair level of awareness but most patients had deficient information about certain aspects and the level of awareness was independent from the socio-demographic and other clinical characteristics of patients.\r\n', '', '', '', 508, 'Rheumatoid Arthritis, Anti-TNF medications, medication awareness', 0, 0, 0, '2024-11-17 08:33:09', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
(1028, '673caaf2b1ff7', 'Laser therapy for Pilonidal Sinus abscess is it safe and effective?', '2024-11-19 15:20:49', '', 1, 'Abstract:\r\nBackground: Pilonidal sinus (PNS) is an inflammatory condition in the natal cleft above the coccyx, often containing hair and debris. Treatment varies and includes observation, drainage, or surgery. This study involved 12 patients with pilonidal sinus abscesses treated using a 1470nm diode laser. The procedure combined abscess drainage with Sinus Laser Therapy (SiLaT).\r\nObjectives: to evaluate the safety and effectiveness of a 1470nm diode laser in treating pilonidal sinus abscesses. \r\nMethods: This prospective study involved 12 patients with pilonidal sinus abscesses, between June 2023 and June 2024 in a private clinic. The patients aged 15 to 32 years, using local anesthesia during the procedures. patients reported any complications via a survey questionnaire.\r\nResults: All patients tolerated the procedure under local anesthesia, with no major complications during the early postoperative period. Sinus pits closed within 12-22 days. The procedure duration ranged from 25-38 minutes. 75% of patients experienced moderate pain and 25% had mild pain. 58.4% of patients had serous discharge for 2-3 days. 66% of patients returned to work after two days, while 34% returned after three days. Overall, 83% of patients were satisfied with the results, while 17% were dissatisfied due to pain.\r\nConclusion:  drainage of pus from pilonidal sinus abscess followed by 1470nm diode laser Sinus Therapy is a safe and effective procedure. It results in minimal postoperative complications. Patients return to work faster than with traditional surgical methods, though recovery is slightly slower than SiLaT alone. \r\n\r\n', '', '', '', 505, '1470nm, pilonidal sinus abscess, pilonidotomy, pilonidoplasty', 0, 0, 0, '2024-11-19 15:20:49', 0, 0, 5, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
