(1030, '673d9a23785a8', 'Sarcopenia Frequency Among a Sample of Iraqi COVID-19 Survivors', '2024-11-20 16:19:51', '', 1, 'Background: The acute stage of Coronavirus disease 2019 induced by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus-2 has had a massive negative impact on the healthcare systems worldwide, but more subtle chronic sequelae are being recognized. Sarcopenia, a progressive loss of muscle mass and strength, is believed to be both a risk factor and a complication of acute COVID-19 in various settings. Objectives: To assess the frequency of sarcopenia and the effect of various patient-related and infection-related factors on its development following COVID-19 infection. Methods: An observational cross-sectional study was conducted at Baghdad Teaching Hospital/ Baghdad, Iraq, from December 2021 to June 2022. A convenience sample of PCR-confirmed infection survivors who were otherwise healthy was recruited. Patients’ data were collected by direct questioning and measurements of muscle mass, strength, and physical performance to determine the sarcopenia category. \r\nResults: 68 participants were included. The mean age was 37.32 years. Severe COVID-19 infection occurred in 12 participants (17.6%) while 56 participants (82.4%) had a non-severe infection. The frequency of sarcopenia was 6% (4 patients), and probable sarcopenia 12% (8 patients). Severe sarcopenia was recorded. The study showed a significant association between sarcopenia and a BMI < 25 (P value 0.023), and between steroid use and probable sarcopenia (P value 0.013). \r\nConclusion: This study shows sarcopenia to be common, and probable sarcopenia to be very common following COVID-19. Having a BMI within the normal range increases the risk of developing sarcopenia and corticosteroid use increases the risk of probable sarcopenia. ', '', '', '', 511, 'sarcopenia, COVID -induced sarcopenia, muscle mass', 0, 0, 0, '2024-11-20 16:19:51', 0, 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0),
